3. Dvapara Yuga (The Bronze Age)

Duration: 864,000 Human Years
Theme: The Age of Doubt and Complexity (Virtue declines by 50%)
Dominant Quality: Tamas & Rajas (Confusion, Ambition)

The "Bull of Dharma" stands on two legs. The world is no longer black and white; it is an era of complex loyalties and tragic choices.

The Fragmentation of Wisdom

The sage Vyasa realizes humanity’s intellect is failing. He divides the one Veda into four, but this fragmentation mirrors the world: families begin to split. The great Kuru dynasty is divided between the five Pandavas and their hundred cousins, the Kauravas.

The Game of Dice: The Loop that Broke the World

The Betrayal: At the heart of this age is a rigged game of dice. The Pandavas lose their kingdom, their freedom, and finally, their wife Draupadi is humiliated in open court. This "open loop" of injustice hangs over the world for thirteen years of exile.

The Negotiator (Krishna): Vishnu descends as Krishna, the divine strategist. He tries to settle the debt through diplomacy, but the Kauravas refuse to give even a "needle-point of land." War becomes the only way to close the loop.

The Great War: The Mahabharata

The Hesitation: On the battlefield of Kurukshetra, the warrior Arjuna falters. How can killing his teachers and kin be "righteous"?

The Song of God: Krishna delivers the Bhagavad Gita, revealing that in a crumbling age, one must perform their duty without attachment.

The Total Destruction: The war lasts 18 days and wipes out almost the entire warrior population of the earth. The Pandavas win, but they inherit a graveyard. The Dvapara Yuga ends with the realization that even a "holy war" leaves the world scarred.
